1201	### 4.8.4 Voice Pooling in AudioWorklet
1202	
1203	Rather than creating/destroying AudioWorklet nodes dynamically (expensive), voice pools pre-allocate a fixed number of processor instances and idle them:
1204	
1205	```typescript
1206	// Main thread: preallocate N voice nodes
1207	const voicePool: AudioWorkletNode[] = [];
1208	for (let i = 0; i < MAX_VOICES; i++) {
1209	  const node = new AudioWorkletNode(audioCtx, 'synth-voice-processor');
1210	  node.connect(masterBus);
1211	  voicePool.push(node);
1212	}
1213	
1214	// On note-on: send 'noteOn' message to selected voice node
1215	function triggerVoice(voiceIdx: number, note: number, velocity: number): void {
1216	  voicePool[voiceIdx].port.postMessage({ type: 'noteOn', note, velocity });
1217	}
1218	```
1219	
1220	The AudioWorklet processor handles note-on by starting its envelope; it handles note-off by starting release. The processor outputs silence (returns a zero buffer) when idle, which the Web Audio API can optimize with "connected graph trimming" in some implementations.
1221	
1222	---
1223	
1224	## 4.9 Preset System
1225	
1226	### 4.9.1 Parameter Serialization
1227	
1228	A preset is a complete serialization of all synthesizer parameters. A flat JSON object is the simplest and most interoperable format:
1229	
1230	```typescript
1231	interface SynthPreset {
1232	  id: string;
1233	  name: string;
1234	  category: string;
1235	  tags: string[];
1236	  version: number;           // schema version for migration
1237	  author?: string;
1238	  createdAt: string;         // ISO 8601
1239	  parameters: Record<string, number | string | boolean>;
1240	  modulationMatrix: ModulationSlot[];
1241	}
1242	```
1243	
1244	Example parameter keys follow a namespaced dot-notation convention:
1245	```
1246	osc1.waveform = "sawtooth"
1247	osc1.detune = 0.0
1248	osc1.octave = 0
1249	filter.type = "lowpass"
1250	filter.cutoff = 800.0
1251	filter.resonance = 0.3
1252	filter.envAmount = 0.5
1253	env1.attack = 10.0      // ms
1254	env1.decay = 200.0      // ms
1255	env1.sustain = 0.7
1256	env1.release = 300.0    // ms
1257	lfo1.rate = 5.0         // Hz
1258	lfo1.depth = 0.3
1259	lfo1.shape = "sine"
1260	```
1261	
1262	### 4.9.2 Factory vs User Presets
1263	
1264	Factory presets are bundled with the application and are read-only. User presets are mutable and stored in IndexedDB (browser) or a backend database. A clean separation:
1265	
1266	```typescript
1267	type PresetSource = 'factory' | 'user';
1268	
1269	interface PresetStore {
1270	  loadPreset(id: string, source: PresetSource): Promise<SynthPreset>;
1271	  savePreset(preset: SynthPreset): Promise<void>;   // only user
1272	  listPresets(category?: string, tags?: string[]): Promise<PresetMeta[]>;
1273	  deletePreset(id: string): Promise<void>;           // only user
1274	}
1275	```
1276	
1277	Preset export/import uses JSON files, enabling sharing between users. A version field in the preset schema allows forward-compatible migration when parameter names or ranges change.
1278	
1279	### 4.9.3 Preset Categories and Tagging
1280	
1281	Standard synthesizer preset categories (borrowed from hardware convention):
1282	- Bass, Lead, Pad, Arpeggio, Sequence, Keys, Organ, Brass, Strings, Percussion, FX, Template
1283	
1284	Tags add freeform metadata: `[warm, dark, modular, vintage, aggressive, ambient, ...]`
1285	
1286	### 4.9.4 Preset Morphing
1287	
1288	Morphing interpolates all numeric parameters between two presets A and B:
1289	
1290	```typescript
1291	function morphPresets(presetA: SynthPreset, presetB: SynthPreset, t: number): SynthPreset {
1292	  const morphed = { ...presetA, parameters: {} };
1293	  for (const key of Object.keys(presetA.parameters)) {
1294	    const a = presetA.parameters[key];
1295	    const b = presetB.parameters[key];
1296	    if (typeof a === 'number' && typeof b === 'number') {
1297	      morphed.parameters[key] = a + (b - a) * t;
1298	    } else {
1299	      // Non-numeric: switch at t = 0.5
1300	      morphed.parameters[key] = t < 0.5 ? a : b;
1301	    }
1302	  }
1303	  return morphed;
1304	}
1305	```
1306	
1307	**Limitations of linear morphing:** Parameters on logarithmic scales (frequency, amplitude) should be interpolated in log space:
1308	
1309	```typescript
1310	function logMorph(a: number, b: number, t: number): number {
1311	  return Math.exp(Math.log(a) + (Math.log(b) - Math.log(a)) * t);
1312	}
1313	```
1314	
1315	---
1316	
1317	## 4.10 Effects Processing
1318	
1319	### 4.10.1 Reverb: Convolution vs Algorithmic
1320	
1321	**Convolution reverb** (impulse response convolution) captures the acoustic character of real spaces. An impulse response (IR) is recorded by firing a starter pistol or sweeping a sine in a space, capturing the room's response. Convolution with this IR applies the exact room acoustics to any audio signal.
1322	
1323	Web Audio API's `ConvolverNode` implements FFT-based overlap-add convolution efficiently:
1324	
1325	```typescript
1326	async function loadIR(audioCtx: AudioContext, irUrl: string): Promise<ConvolverNode> {
1327	  const response = await fetch(irUrl);
1328	  const arrayBuffer = await response.arrayBuffer();
1329	  const audioBuffer = await audioCtx.decodeAudioData(arrayBuffer);
1330	  const convolver = audioCtx.createConvolver();
1331	  convolver.buffer = audioBuffer;
1332	  return convolver;
1333	}
1334	```
1335	
1336	**Algorithmic reverb** synthesizes reverberation from a network of delay lines, comb filters, and allpass filters. The Schroeder (1962) model uses parallel comb filters (for density) followed by series allpass filters (for diffusion):
1337	
1338	```
1339	// Freeverb (Jezar at Dreampoint, 1997) -- 8 comb + 4 allpass per channel
1340	// Comb filter:
1341	y[n] = x[n-delay] + g * y[n-delay] + (1-g) * damping * x[n-delay]
1342	
1343	// Allpass filter:
1344	y[n] = -g * x[n] + x[n-delay] + g * y[n-delay]
1345	```
1346	
1347	Freeverb parameters: `roomSize` (0-1 maps comb filter gains), `damping` (high-frequency absorption), `wet` (reverb level), `width` (stereo spread).
1348	
1349	**Trade-offs:**
1350	
1351	| Feature            | Convolution        | Algorithmic (Freeverb) |
1352	|-------------------|--------------------|------------------------|
1353	| Realism           | High (authentic)   | Medium (synthetic)     |
1354	| CPU cost          | High (FFT per block)| Low                   |
1355	| Memory            | High (IR buffer)   | Minimal                |
1356	| Adjustability     | Limited (EQ only)  | Full parameter control |
1357	| Latency           | Block-size (ConvolverNode) | Sample-accurate |
1358	
1359	### 4.10.2 Delay
1360	
1361	**Simple delay:** A circular buffer of audio samples. Output is the sample at position `(writePos - delayInSamples)`.
1362	
1363	```typescript
1364	class DelayLine {
1365	  private buffer: Float32Array;
1366	  private writePos = 0;
1367	
1368	  constructor(maxDelaySeconds: number, sampleRate: number) {
1369	    this.buffer = new Float32Array(Math.ceil(maxDelaySeconds * sampleRate));
1370	  }
1371	
1372	  process(input: number, delayInSamples: number, feedback: number): number {
1373	    const readPos = (this.writePos - delayInSamples + this.buffer.length) % this.buffer.length;
1374	    const output = this.buffer[readPos];
1375	    this.buffer[this.writePos] = input + output * feedback;
1376	    this.writePos = (this.writePos + 1) % this.buffer.length;
1377	    return output;
1378	  }
1379	}
1380	```
1381	
1382	**Ping-pong delay:** Two delay lines (left/right channels) where the left output feeds the right input and vice versa, creating a bouncing stereo delay effect.
1383	
1384	**Tape delay:** A modulated delay line where the delay time changes slowly (simulating tape speed variation), plus a lowpass filter in the feedback loop (simulating tape bandwidth limitation), plus a saturation stage (simulating tape saturation).
1385	
1386	### 4.10.3 Distortion and Waveshaping
1387	
1388	Distortion is implemented as a nonlinear waveshaping function applied sample-by-sample:
1389	
1390	```typescript
1391	type WaveshapeFn = (x: number) => number;
1392	
1393	// Soft clipping (tanh saturation)
1394	const softClip: WaveshapeFn = (x) => Math.tanh(x * drive) / Math.tanh(drive);
1395	
1396	// Hard clipping
1397	const hardClip: WaveshapeFn = (x) => Math.max(-1, Math.min(1, x * drive));
1398	
1399	// Asymmetric soft clip (tube-like even harmonics)
1400	const tubeSat: WaveshapeFn = (x) => {
1401	  if (x >= 0) return 1 - Math.exp(-x);
1402	  return -1 + Math.exp(x * 0.5);  // softer on negative side
1403	};
1404	
1405	// Precompute lookup table for real-time use (avoid Math.tanh per sample)
1406	function makeWaveshapeTable(fn: WaveshapeFn, tableSize = 4096): Float32Array {
1407	  const table = new Float32Array(tableSize);
1408	  for (let i = 0; i < tableSize; i++) {
1409	    const x = (i / tableSize) * 2 - 1;
1410	    table[i] = fn(x);
1411	  }
1412	  return table;
1413	}
1414	```
1415	
1416	**Oversampling for distortion:** Waveshaping generates harmonics above Nyquist. For high-quality distortion, upsample the signal 2x-8x before waveshaping, then downsample with a steep lowpass filter. Web Audio API does not provide native oversampling for custom processors; it must be implemented manually in the AudioWorklet or via the WaveShaper node's `oversample` property (`'none'`, `'2x'`, `'4x'`).
1417	
1418	The native `WaveShaperNode` accepts a Float32Array curve and applies it with optional oversampling -- suitable for moderate distortion needs without custom AudioWorklet code.
1419	
1420	### 4.10.4 Chorus, Flanger, Phaser
1421	
1422	All three are modulated delay effects:
1423	
1424	**Chorus:** A short modulated delay (10-30 ms) mixed with the dry signal. The modulation (LFO at 0.1-5 Hz) creates pitch variation, thickening the sound. Multiple delay taps with different LFO phases give a wider, richer chorus.
1425	
1426	**Flanger:** An extremely short modulated delay (0.5-10 ms) with feedback, creating a comb-filter sweep. The LFO sweep moves the comb filter notches up and down.
1427	
1428	**Phaser:** An allpass filter bank whose center frequencies are modulated by an LFO. Instead of delay, it creates phase shifts at specific frequencies, and when mixed with dry signal, produces comb-filter-like cancellations that sweep in pitch.
1429	
1430	```typescript
1431	// All-pass filter for phaser
1432	class AllpassFilter {
1433	  private state = 0;
1434	
1435	  process(input: number, coeff: number): number {
1436	    // First-order allpass: output = -g*input + x[n-1] + g*y[n-1]
1437	    const output = coeff * (input - this.state) + this.state;
1438	    this.state = input;
1439	    return output;
1440	  }
1441	}
1442	
1443	class Phaser {
1444	  private stages: AllpassFilter[] = Array.from({ length: 4 }, () => new AllpassFilter());
1445	  private lfo: LFO;
1446	
1447	  tick(input: number): number {
1448	    const lfoValue = this.lfo.tick();
1449	    // Map LFO to allpass coefficient range
1450	    const coeff = lfoToCoeff(lfoValue);
1451	    let x = input;
1452	    for (const stage of this.stages) {
1453	      x = stage.process(x, coeff);
1454	    }
1455	    return (input + x) * 0.5; // mix dry + processed
1456	  }
1457	}
1458	```
1459	
1460	### 4.10.5 Compressor/Limiter
1461	
1462	**DynamicsCompressorNode** provides an efficient native compressor with parameters: `threshold`, `knee`, `ratio`, `attack`, `release`, `reduction`. Suitable for bus compression and final limiter.
1463	
1464	**Custom compressor** in AudioWorklet allows sidechain, lookahead, and per-sample gain computation:
1465	
1466	```typescript
1467	// Sidechain compressor (simplified)
1468	class Compressor {
1469	  private envelope = 0;
1470	  private threshold: number;   // linear
1471	  private ratio: number;
1472	  private attackCoeff: number;
1473	  private releaseCoeff: number;
1474	
1475	  tick(input: number, sidechain: number): number {
1476	    // Level detection (RMS or peak)
1477	    const level = Math.abs(sidechain);
1478	
1479	    // Envelope follower
1480	    const coeff = level > this.envelope ? this.attackCoeff : this.releaseCoeff;
1481	    this.envelope = this.envelope + coeff * (level - this.envelope);
1482	
1483	    // Gain computation
1484	    let gainDb = 0;
1485	    if (this.envelope > this.threshold) {
1486	      gainDb = (this.threshold - this.envelope) * (1 - 1 / this.ratio);
1487	    }
1488	    const gainLinear = Math.pow(10, gainDb / 20);
1489	    return input * gainLinear;
1490	  }
1491	}
1492	```
1493	
1494	**Lookahead limiter:** Delays the audio signal by L samples (lookahead time), while computing the gain reduction from the undelayed signal. This allows the limiter to react to peaks before they arrive, preventing any overshoots.
1495	
1496	### 4.10.6 EQ
1497	
1498	**Parametric EQ** applies a cascade of biquad filters (each targeting a specific frequency band):
1499	
1500	```typescript
1501	class ParametricEQ {
1502	  private bands: BiquadFilter[];
1503	
1504	  constructor(bandCount: number) {
1505	    this.bands = Array.from({ length: bandCount }, () => new BiquadFilter());
1506	    // Band 0: low shelf, band N-1: high shelf, middle: peak EQ
1507	  }
1508	
1509	  setBand(index: number, freq: number, gain: number, Q: number, sampleRate: number): void {
1510	    const band = this.bands[index];
1511	    if (index === 0) band.setLowShelf(freq, gain, sampleRate);
1512	    else if (index === this.bands.length - 1) band.setHighShelf(freq, gain, sampleRate);
1513	    else band.setPeak(freq, gain, Q, sampleRate);
1514	  }
1515	
1516	  process(input: number): number {
1517	    return this.bands.reduce((x, band) => band.process(x), input);
1518	  }
1519	}
1520	```
1521	
1522	**Graphic EQ** uses a fixed set of center frequencies (typically ISO octave or 1/3-octave) with individual boost/cut controls. Each band is a peak filter with fixed Q (approximately 1.41 for octave spacing, 4.32 for 1/3-octave spacing).
